      "en": {
        "file": "35_autres_forces.md",
        "title": "磨盘劲 · mò pán jìn",
        "markdown": "## 磨盘劲 · mò pán jìn\n\n### The Millstone Force\n\n---\n\n> When the millstone turns, the opponent overturns himself.\n\n— Traditional saying\n\n---\n\n## The Essence of Mò Pán Jìn\n\nMò Pán Jìn is neither a circular push nor a localized rotation of the arms.\n\nThe old masters describe it as:\n\n· a circle that engages the entire body,\n\n· a rotation that rises from the ground and passes through the pelvis,\n\n· a force that never leaves its axis,\n\n· and that wears down the opponent's structure without ever striking it.\n\nMò Pán Jìn does not project outward.\n\nIt remains.\n\nAnd it is what remains that grinds.\n\n---\n\n## Fundamental Principles\n\n1\\. The millstone turns; it does not push\n\nThe millstone does not push the grain. It turns. The grain places itself between the stones, and the rotation does the rest. One does not seek to displace the opponent; one turns in place, massively, and everything resting upon that rotation gradually loses its supports.\n\n2\\. The movement comes from the ground, not the arms\n\nThe apparent rotation is only the surface. The true engine is in the feet, the hips, the pelvis, the spine. The arms merely accompany. If the arms turn without the pelvis, the millstone does not exist.\n\n3\\. Slowness is the condition of efficacy\n\nMò Pán Jìn tolerates no haste. A rapid rotation breaks the internal connection, alerts the opponent, transforms the millstone into a mere circular strike. Slow rotation maintains continuity, absorbs resistances, wears away without the other perceiving the exact moment of his loss.\n\n4\\. The axis does not move\n\nThe millstone possesses a fixed center. In Mò Pán Jìn, the practitioner's center does not shift, the root does not lift, the breath does not rise. If the axis moves, the force disperses. If the axis remains, the rotation becomes irresistible.\n\n5\\. The force grinds without destroying\n\nMò Pán Jìn does not seek brutal rupture. It wears away supports, balance, internal structure. The opponent feels no shock. He feels the ground turning beneath him, his center shifting without reason, his force finding no point of support. Then he falls. Not because he has been overturned, but because the ground under him has changed.\n\n---\n\n## The Levels of Mò Pán Jìn\n\n**Beginner level:** The rotation is still localized. The shoulders or arms initiate the circle. The opponent can resist by rooting.\n\n**Intermediate level:** The pelvis becomes the engine. The rotation passes through the spine. The opponent feels a turning pressure, but can still retreat.\n\n**Advanced level:** The rotation rises from the feet. The entire body becomes a single millstone. The opponent can neither advance, nor retreat, nor turn. He rests upon a plane that moves as a whole. He loses all orientation.\n\n---\n\n## Final Summary\n\nMò Pán Jìn is not an arm technique. It is not a local twist. It is not a decorative circle. It is a rotation of the entire body, rooted in the ground, directed by the pelvis, carried by an immobile axis, that gradually wears away the opponent's supports and structure.\n\nThe true Mò Pán Jìn appears slow, remains massive, shows no violence, yet transforms all opposition into dust."
      },
      "zh": {
        "file": "35_autres_forces.md",
        "title": "磨盘劲 · mò pán jìn",
        "markdown": "## 磨盘劲 · mò pán jìn\n\n### The Millstone Force\n\n**定义。** 磨盘劲是一种全身旋转的劲力，通过固定中轴和身体整体转动，逐渐砍磨对方的结构与平衡，而非直接冲击。\n\n**详细说明。** 磨盘劲的核心在于“转而非推”。像磨盘磨粉一样，旋转本身产生砍磨力，而不是通过推挤对方。旋转从脚底发动，经跨、腰、脊柱，最终传至双臂。手臂仅仅是伴随者，而非发动机。\n\n**身体机制。** 脚跟稳定粘于地面，中轴不动，跨部引导旋转，脊柱顺势传递力量。肩膀放松，手臂随着身体整体旋转而动，不单独发力。\n\n**练习。** 先练习站桩静转，感受从脚到手的力量传递。然后加入伙伴，在推手中保持轻微接触，让对方感受到“地面在转”的错觉，而不是被推。\n\n**技击应用。** 在推手中用于砍磨对方根基，使其逐渐失去平衡，最终自行倒地。\n\n**常见错误。** 用手臂单独旋转、腰跨不参与、转速过快丧失连续性、中心移动。\n\n**掌握标志。** 旋转从脚底发动，全身成为一个整体磨盘，对方无法判断力量方向和来源。"
      }
